'''Lambertus Johannes Hermanus "Bart" Becht''' (born 29 July 1956)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukdata.com/director/detail/916600464|title=Company and Director credit reports and annual accounts. Free search. - All UK Directors. Business credit reports|publisher=|accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fam-lameris.net/becht/becht_x.htm|title=Parenteel Johann Andreas Becht (X) [1736-??]|publisher=|accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> is a Dutch businessman. Becht is the [[former]] [[CEO]] of [[Reckitt Benckiser]], a company he headed from its creation in 1999 through to his retirement in 2011.
==Early life== Becht studied economics at the [[University of Groningen]], The Netherlands, and took an MBA at [[Rotterdam School of Management]], [[Erasmus University]] and the [[University of Chicago]].
==Career== He joined the Benckiser side of the business in 1988, following a career at [[Procter & Gamble]].<ref name="Guardian">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2010/apr/07/profile-bart-becht-reckitt-benckiser|title=Profile: Bart Becht, chief executive of Reckitt Benckiser|last=Treanor|first=Jill|date=7 April 2010|work=guardian.co.uk|accessdate=29 May 2010}}</ref>
Some of the schemes that helped take his pay to £90m<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2010/may/05/reckitt-benckiser-pay-deal|title=How a heroin substitute helped to fuel profits for Reckitt Benckiser chief|last=Bowers|first=Simon|author2=Ian Griffiths|date=5 May 2010|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 May 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100509050548/http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2010/may/05/reckitt-benckiser-pay-deal|archivedate=9 May 2010|deadurl=no|df=}}</ref> in 2009 date back to the formation in 1999, during which time Becht prided himself on the [[share price]] performance and [[Profit (accounting)|profitability]]. Over the 10 years to 2010, the company was the fourth best performing stock in the [[FTSE 100]].<ref name="Guardian" />
He retired as CEO of Reckitt Benckiser on 31 August 2011, and was succeeded by [[Rakesh Kapoor]].
== Personal life == Becht, who is married and has three children, gave many of the shares he was awarded to a [[charitable trust]] that donates primarily to [[humanitarian]] causes. {{cn|date=April 2016}}
