'''John Cockburn''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|oʊ|b|ər|n}} {{respell|KOH|bərn}}) of [[Ormiston]], [[East Lothian]], (died 12 November 1758) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] landowner and politician who sat in the [[Parliament of Scotland]] from 1702 to 1707 and in the [[British House of Commons]] for 34 years from 1707 to 1741.

[[File:Ormiston Hall.jpg|thumb|Ormiston Hall, prior to the WWII fire which left it in ruins]]
He was the son of [[Adam Cockburn of Ormiston]], [[Lord Justice Clerk]], who he succeeded in 1735. He is known as the father of Scottish [[husbandry]].

Cockburn became a member of the [[Parliament of Scotland|Scottish Parliament]] and took an active interest in accomplishing the union. He was the first representative of [[Haddingtonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Lothian]] in the parliament of the [[Kingdom of Great Britain|United Kingdom of Great Britain]], and continued to hold that seat in all successive parliaments until 1741. He was one of the [[Lords Commissioners of the Admiralty]]. <ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/cockburn-john-1679-1758| title= COCKBURN, John (c.1679-1758), of Ormiston, Haddington.| publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate =15 August 2018}}</ref>

He built [[Ormiston Hall]] on his estate at [[Ormiston]]. This last Cockburn of Ormiston was an enthusiastic entrepreneur and eventually ruined himself as a result of which his estates were sold to the Earl of Hopetoun.

John Cockburn of Ormiston died in his son's house in the [[Navy Board|Navy Office]], London, England. He had firstly married Beatrix, daughter of [[John Carmichael, 1st Earl of Hyndford]], by whom he had no issue and secondly married Arabella, the daughter and coheiress of Anthony Rowe of Muswell Hall, Middlesex, with whom he had a son. His natural son, [[George Cockburne]] (d.1770), was a [[Captain (Royal Navy)|captain]] in the [[Royal Navy]], and married Caroline, daughter of George Forrester, 5th Lord Forrester, with female issue.

